### Hash Tree (Persistent Data Structure)

In the grim, unforgiving landscape of computer science, there exists a peculiar construct known as a [hash tree](/Trie), or sometimes, a hash [trie](/Trie). It’s a [persistent data structure](/Persistent_data_structure), which means it remembers its past, unlike so many ephemeral things. Its purpose? To serve as a replacement for the… *mundane* [hash tables](/Hash_table), particularly in the sterile, uncompromising world of [purely functional programming](/Purely_functional_programming).

At its core, this hash tree is a bit of a minimalist. It doesn't bother with the actual keys directly. Instead, it stores the [hashes](/Hash_function) of these keys. Think of the keys as strings of bits, a language only machines truly understand. These hashes are then meticulously organized within a trie structure. The real keys, and any associated values you might have grudgingly attached, are relegated to the "final" nodes of this trie. They’re the caboose on a train of abstract concepts. &#91;1&#93;

Now, this basic hash tree isn’t the end of the story. Oh no. There are refined versions, like [hash array mapped tries](/Hash_array_mapped_trie) and [Ctries](/Ctrie). They’re essentially upgraded models, employing particular, more sophisticated implementations of the trie. More intricate, perhaps, but still built on the same bleak foundation. &#91;1&#93;

